[16:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'recommend using Aurora, but you also have HeyGen Avatar 4 directly inside of the platform as well. And you also can create multiple generations. I don\'t recommend doing that, and I\'m going to'

[16:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'talk about why in just a second. Let\'s go ahead and click generate. Okay, let\'s take a look at our video clips here. This is the version we got from Aurora. &gt;&gt; Clean 2.0 is here and it\'s taking over social media, but the big question is,'

[16:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'how does it stack up against other AI video tools? Okay, so the lip syncing is pretty good. I think the overall performance feels definitely much more synthetic than what you would expect'

[16:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'from a real live-action video clip, but I could see, especially if you needed a very staged shot where your character\'s just speaking directly to the camera, and you don\'t need a lot of enthusiasm,'

[17:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'maybe you could get something usable in a few use cases, but I would probably not rely on [music] this. Now, let\'s compare that to HeyGen. HeyGen gave us this. "Clean 2.0 is here, and it\'s taking over social media. But, the big'

[17:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'question is how does it stack up against other AI video tools?" And it\'s really funny because usually I would say that HeyGen is a better video model for lip-syncing, but in this case, there\'s a lot of weird stuff happening with the'

[17:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'teeth where there\'s morphing around it. And because us as humans we\'re looking at eyeballs and teeth most of the time when we were looking at a presenter, it\'s just warping in a really weird way. Another thing I want to point out is'

[17:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'earlier we generated multiple versions of each video clip here. And so, I have the panel view pulled up here. You can see we have the two HeyGen generations at the top and the two Aurora generations in that middle row. And you'

[18:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'can see that the expression is the exact same between both of the video clips. The one on the left and the one on the right is the exact same. And that shouldn\'t necessarily be the case. That only is the case usually if you\'re not'

[18:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'getting a different seeded generation. Remember, when you\'re generating inside an AI image or video platform, they almost always have a tag that\'s the seed that is generating basically a new'

[18:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'random generation every single time. Sometimes you can lock that seed down and you\'ll get the same type of generation, and it allows you to make smaller procedural changes to the video or image so that you have more control'

[18:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'over the output time and time again. But, in this case, it\'s not actually ideal because it doesn\'t change the variation in the video that\'s generated. And so, you\'re basically just kind of wasting credits if you select any amount'

[18:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of generation beyond one. So, I would think that the Eleven Labs team is probably going to fix that in the near future. But, just something to keep an eye out for because you probably would end up wasting credits. In image generation news, the team at Reeve has'

[19:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'released a brand new AI image model that is a very real competitor to the very best models on the market. Now, when the first iteration of Reeve came out, it was incredible because it was one of the'

[19:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'very first image models that gave you really good text results. Remember, back in the early days, all the way back when Midjourney was the best model on the market, the text was absolutely bonkers.'

[19:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And in fact, the text is still bonkers over on Midjourney, but Reeve has always really given you much more control as a creative professional. But in the era of Nano Banana, what does that actually'

[19:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'mean? Well, let\'s take a look inside their platform and I want to show you a really cool feature that they have for layer-based editing that is really innovative and I think a really smart'

[19:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'way to go about the creative process. So, I\'m here on the Reeve website and have a long prompt here. I\'m not going to read it all. It\'s basically a DJ performing in a club. And from here, of course, you can change various aspects'

[20:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of the image from aspect ratio to the number of images that you are creating. And they also have a references feature that allows you to do character and style reference if you want for your [music] image project. And we\'ll go'

[20:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'ahead and click render. Now, this is the image that was generated inside of Reeve and it\'s really compelling. What I like about this image is the fact that it does look just more interesting from a'

[20:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'composition and lighting perspective than the same result that we got from Nano Banana. Inside of Nano, we got this image which just has that very flat, almost stock photo lighting that you get'

[20:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'almost time and time again whenever you only use prompt alone. And that\'s why we almost always use stylistic references from other AI image models to like Midjourney or real-life images whenever we\'re really looking to push the style'

[21:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'in a direction that goes beyond stock photography, which is almost 100% of the time. So, the cool thing is you do have the ability now to go in and lock down certain aspects of your scene that you want to keep intact and then change'

[21:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'other elements. So, we can go in and we can lock the man, we can lock the mixer, the turntable, and the crowd, but all of the light streaks we don\'t have to include. And we can ask Reeve to remove'

[21:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the light streaks and go ahead and click render. And that gives us this image, which is okay. I don\'t know if the edits are quite as good as Nano Banana, but the fact that you have much more control is, you know, really compelling,'

[21:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'especially if you\'re working on a high-end film project where maximum control is just really, really helpful. So, I think it did a good job. The one thing I will note is because we got rid of the light leaks, that does make the scene not really look like a long'

[21:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'exposure image, and so just these random faces that all just kind of morphed together are just really, really uncanny. So, I think the light trails were kind of helping a little bit there. And we can also take that original image and say swap his shirt to purple, and'

[22:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'after a few seconds it created this image here, and just the lighting, the compositing, everything looks very, very realistic. So, it did a really good job. I\'m not sure if Nano Bananas operating under the surface or something else, but'

[22:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'whatever it is, it\'s doing a really good job. So, let\'s look at a couple other examples here inside of Reeve. We had this picture of this little boy, we asked to swap with a picture of a girl on the carousel, and it gave us this,'

[22:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'which looks basically photorealistic. Like it\'s doing a really, really good job. If I gave it any critique, it\'d be that it\'s a little more staged than I\'d like it to be, but it looks very realistic. So, really good job from'

[22:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Reeve. And so, I wanted to go in and compare it against some of the other image generation tools on the market. So, we\'re taking a look at GPT-2, Nano Banana 2, and Reeve 2 here. So, we prompted for a 1985 Mac computer here,'

[22:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and [music] it gave us this inside of GPT-2, which looks pretty solid. Like even the text is just really good. This person is just really into Macs. And'

[23:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'inside of Nano Banana 2, we got this image here. Again, it does come across as a bit more staged, but it\'s not bad. It\'s doing a really good job here. I do think the the text in Nano Banana 2 can'

[23:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'always somewhat come across as a bit more like a font as opposed to just naturalistic text that you would see inside of the scene, but it\'s not bad. And we got this from Reeve 2.0. Again,'

[23:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Reeve 2.0 is doing a pretty decent job. I do think there\'s something strange going on here on the the cover of this book, but all things considered, it\'s'

[23:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'doing a pretty decent job. I don\'t think it\'s the best, but it\'s definitely very competitive against those other two tools on the market. And the fact that they have a nowhere close to the amount of resources that OpenAI or Google has'

[23:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'means that I think that pound for pound they\'re doing incredible stuff over at Reeve. Let\'s take a look at a cinematic example. So I prompted for [music] just kind of this peasant guy looking over a lagoon here with a light. We got this'

[24:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'from GPT-2, which does look good, although there\'s some artifacting that I don\'t love. Inside of Nano Banana 2, we got this, which I think maybe did a better job in this case. And then inside'

