[24:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'honest, I haven\'t seen a lot of mantis shrimp in my life, but if I saw this image, I would probably assume that it\'s a real photo of a shrimp here. So, I\'ll call it a tie between all of the shots, but I have a nagging suspicion that'

[25:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'GPT-2 probably did the best job. In omnimodel news, we came across something this last week that kind of knocked our socks off. So, we\'ve been talking a lot about omnimodels over the last few months. If you\'re not already familiar,'

[25:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'an omnimodel typically allows you to take a creative media asset, whether it\'s a video, audio clip, or image, bring it into a model, type in a prompt, &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; and then it will output a specific media type in return. All of Google\'s creative'

[25:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'tools are kind of working towards the system where you can upload a huge amount of data into the model and output basically anything you want, whether it\'s a 3D world, a game, a video, an image, or anything in between. But,'

[25:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'specifically, video versions of omnimodels have been very popular, whether it\'s C-DANCE Omni or Ray 3.2 from Luma. They\'re really interesting because they allow you to upload video footage and then make changes, whether'

[25:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'they\'re small changes or large changes directly inside [music] the platform. However, the team at NVIDIA announced a brand new tool called Sona Streaming that makes these omnimodel changes to'

[26:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'your video in real time. So, you\'re not uploading a video clip and hitting render, you\'re literally changing a live video feed. Now, of course, you could then take pre-rendered video footage and'

[26:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'run it through the model, but I want to show you a few examples of this real-time model in action and talk about what this means for the future of video. So, you\'ll find a link below this video to check out the Sona Streaming page, and you can actually download the code'

[26:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'for yourself. This entire project was a collaboration between NVIDIA, MIT, and a bunch of other people that are 10 times smarter than I will ever be. So, the value proposition with this tool is basically you have the ability to take'

[26:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'inputted video footage, again, this can be live video footage and output 24 frames per second at 704p. So, almost HD quality. And again, this is now, you can imagine just months from'

[27:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'now, the technology is going to continue to progress here. So, there\'s a few different examples over on their website. For example, we have the shot of this guy in this room here and he\'s looking around and he prompted for'

[27:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'sunglasses to be on his face and it\'s real-time tracking the sunglasses directly [music] into the scene here. They also prompted to change the style from real-time video to this like Van Gogh style and again,'

[27:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it\'s doing this all in real-time. From a visual effects example, they typed in a prompt to remove the earring from this woman\'s ear and it is removing it in real-time. They also typed in a prompt'

[27:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to change the clothing of a character and you can see it automatically [music] did that. It also gets into real-time production changes and so we have this character in a black studio environment and typed it in a prompt just to put'

[27:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'them inside a kind of [music] white futuristic room here and you can see it\'s making those changes to the character. Again, this is not pixel-perfect quality at this point, but the fact that it\'s doing this'

[28:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'automatically right now is pretty crazy. They also tested out some environmental changes that I think could be a little better. And it also can do real-time rotoscoping. So, we have the woman'

[28:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'standing here with the man, type in a prompt to remove her from the video stream and she\'s removed. So, with all of this being said, what does this mean for the future of Omni models and visual effects utilizing AI? Long story short,'

[28:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'as we get into a lower latency environment, as it takes less and less time for you to type in a prompt and see the result from these AI video tools, that will allow you to stay in deeper'

[28:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'flow states whenever you are working on a film project. One of the biggest criticisms of the current agentic platform workflow that so many tool companies are promoting is the fact that it is much much slower than you just'

[28:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'hopping into a flow state inside an aggregation tool. Or if you need to make changes to a video clip, again, it\'s going to take multiple minutes to begin to get that iterative feedback. But if you can work inside a video editing'

[29:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'application to type in a change and see that change in real time and then uprez the change using a completely different AI generation tool, that is going to allow you to be in a creative flow state'

[29:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and do incredible things. I also can only imagine what this is going to be able to do for real-time sporting events or live interactive experiences. We are just at the tip of the iceberg of what'

